ning federal copyright as it was under the Copyright Act of 1909  No publication or registration or other action in the Copyright Office is required to secure copyright  Copyright Endurance Generally  copyright extends from the moment of a work s creation to 70 years after the author s death  See the document  Copyright Basics pp  5 6  below  for a more extensive treatment  Links to Copyright Information The Library of Congress maintains an extensive repository of copyright information  Some of the more informative documents for educators are the following  Copyright Basics requires Adobe Acrobat Reader  Reproduction of Copyrighted Works by Educators and Librarians  requires Adobe Acrobat Reader  Copyright FAQ  Frequently Asked Questions  Title 17 of US Code  Copyright statutes  The Digital Millenium Copyright Act  long 50 pp  PDF  The DMCA Summary Copyright Registration Information Copyright Registration for Sound Recordings Copyright Infringement Allegations and Agents The Interlibrary Loan office in Preston Library maintains copies of these works      Copyright Policy The following is offered in an attempt to make faculty  cadets  and staff more aware of copyright law and policy and our responsibilities towards it  For more extensive explanations and treatments of copyright law  policy  and rights and responsibilities  refer to the documents cited below  Definition Copyright is a form of protection provided by the laws of the United States  title 17  U S  Code  to the authors of  original works of authorship  including literary  dramatic  musical  artistic  and certain other intellectual works  This protection is available to both published and unpublished works  The Copyright Act of 1976 replaced the Act of 1909  Copyright Claim Copyright protection subsists from the time the work is created in fixed form  The copyright in the work of authorship immediately becomes the property of the author who created the work  Only the author or those deriving their rights th